Not exactly. There are two &quot;types&quot; of mass: &quot;relativistic mass&quot; (here, &quot;M&quot;) and &quot;rest mass&quot; (here, &quot;m&quot;). MinutePhysics (validly) using the term &quot;mass&quot; to mean &quot;rest mass.&quot;

The two masses are related by the equation M^2 = m^2 / (1 - (v^2/c^2)). 

Photons have no rest mass (m=0), so their relativistic mass is given by M^2 = (0)^2 / (1 - (v^2/c^2)). For all v=/=c, this is zero: if a photon is not traveling at the speed of light, it has no mass, no energy, and no momentum - it does not exist.

Actually, that depends on how you define &quot;mass.&quot; MinutePhysics uses the word &quot;mass&quot; to mean &quot;rest mass,&quot; which is an object&#39;s mass in its own frame of reference. Photons have a rest mass of 0, so they are called &quot;massless.&quot;

However, &quot;massless&quot; particles do have another type of mass - &quot;relativistic mass.&quot; That is the mass that an observer measures the thing to have.

Also, you can divide zero by zero - it just lacks a specific answer. E.g., contrast 5=0/0 (i.e., 5*0=0) with x=2/0 (i.e., 0*x=2).

